Once free will is carefully defined, the free will vs. determinism debate resolves itself completely. We do have free will (defined as evitability or similar)[1]; we don't have free will (defined as freedom physics).

The meme that there is an unresovable conflict between free will and determinism remains sticky in culture even though it isn't widely considered a big issue in contemporary philosophy of mind. The idea that there isn't really a conflict is called compatibilism[2]; the opposite being incompatibilism.

[1]: Dan Dennett's Freedom Evolves is good for this.
[2]: https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/compatibilism/

The Dennett book is pretty accessible. You may enjoy reading it.

The question is basically: free will is freedom from what? We are obviously not free from physics (the view of determinism); we are just physical things.

But if "free will" means something else ("evitability") then maybe both views are compatible.

Magi 🟠 is a new OP Stack client for the Optimism ecosystem. Written in Rust, we hope it serves as a fast alternative to @OPLabsPBC's op-node.

🔢 client diversity = robust decentralization
🧩 more languages = more engineers
🦀 Rust = safe and fast

github.com/a16z/magi

Like Ethereum, the OP Stack requires two clients types to run: an execution client like op-geth + a consensus client like op-node. And now, Magi.

In the future, these clients might be mixed and matched both to improve client diversity and to offer specific technical features. https://i.imgur.com/24hfI02.png

With more clients, the Optimism ecosystem becomes more varied and resilient — more able to endure bugs and other challenges, but also more flexible and able to evolve.

Think about single-species monoculture vs. a natural rainforest. Only one can support a thriving ecosystem. https://i.imgur.com/1hMV4Mo.jpg

🚧 Magi is under construction and not to be used in a production environment. 🚧

According to the crypto ethos, we want to build it out in the open and hope that you can help us. We welcome all contributions — from docs to designs.

Story Protocol is dear to my heart — you could describe it as a hyperstructure for making composable creative works. The terms of securing rights on a work are clear and preserve attribution, so any downstream monetization can trickle upstream properly.

https://twitter.com/StoryProtocol/status/1699411637244158037

Creative works want to be remixed and recombined, but the current IP system makes this difficult. What if you could produce works and push them onchain into a protocol that preserves ownership, makes terms for using the IP clear and legible, and makes it easy to receive payment if someone monetizes it down the line?

Onchain is perfect: we can preserve the attribution graph, define the terms of recomposition, ensure the protocol remains credibly neutral (no platform risk for creatives) — and we can even route payments through this graph. Producing new creative works becomes more permissionless, and more composable.
Yeah, it's like minting. Except we need to track various metadata, verify ownership of the IP, and a few other things. So it will be more complex than minting, but basically the same idea.

There are definitely some overlaps — there is much to improve in how we create and reward media production — but their target users and initial focuses are totally different. They'll probably end up drifting even further apart as they search for PMF.
